{{more footnotes|date=August 2013}} {{use mdy dates|date=August 2013}} {{Infobox artist | name = Gilberto Hernández Ortega | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = 21 December 1923<ref>{{cite web|title=Biografía|url=http://www.hdezortega.org/biografia/|publisher=Memoria H'dez Ortega|accessdate=25 July 2017|date=18 December 2015}}</ref> | birth_place = [[Baní]], [[Peravia Province]], [[Dominican Republic]] | death_date = {{dda|1979|10|23|1923|12|21|df=y}} | death_place = [[Santo Domingo]], Dominican Republic | nationality = | spouse = | field = [[Painting]] | training = [[National School of Fine Arts]] | movement = [[Surrealism]] | works = | patrons = | awards = | elected = }} '''Gilberto Hernández Ortega''' (21 December 1923 &ndash; 23 October 1979) was an artist from the [[Dominican Republic]]. He is considered a leading [[painting|painter]] of his generation.
==Early life and education== He was born in [[Baní]], [[Peravia Province]], in 1923 but was raised in [[Santo Domingo]]. Ortega first studied art under [[Celeste Woss y Gil]] at her private academy. Undecided about his career, he studied [[engineering]] for more than two years before committing to pursuing painting. He enrolled in the [[National School of Fine Arts]], where he studied under Woss y Gil once again, as well as [[Josep Gausachs]] and [[George Hausdorf]]. Ortega was particularly influenced by Gausachs, maintaining a close relationship with the older artist until Gausachs's death in 1959. In addition to Gausachs, he worked closely with [[Jaime Colson]] and [[Clara Ledesma]]. Other sources of inspiration included [[Cuba]]n artists [[Wifredo Lam]] and [[Mario Carreño Morales]].
==Career== [[File:Hernandez Ortega 01.jpg|left|thumb|Untitled, oil on canvas, 1976 ([[Museo Bellapart]], Santo Domingo)|261x261px]] In 1946, Ortega had his first solo exhibition, exhibiting 63 paintings and drawings. He also exhibited abroad, with his first international solo exhibition being held in [[Caracas]], [[Venezuela]], in 1951. Other international shows included exhibitions in the United States, Spain, Argentina, Brazil, Israel and Taiwan. In addition, he was awarded prizes in national Biennial art events in 1952, 1958 and 1974.
He also taught art for many years. Ortega became a professor at the National School of Fine Arts in 1946 and was named vice director in 1954. In 1966, he opened a private art school in Santo Domingo. During his many years of teaching, Ortega had a significant influence on major Dominican artists, including [[Ada Balcácer]], [[Iván Tovar]], [[Ramón Oviedo]] and [[Elsa Núñez]].
While primarily a [[Surrealist]], he also experimented with [[Expressionism]] and [[Abstraction]]. Most of Ortega's paintings are [[figurative art|figurative]], depicting distorted human forms. Although dark colors such as blues, violets, grays, greens, browns and black predominate, his [[Color scheme|palette]] is often enlivened with vibrant yellows, oranges and reds.
==Death== Ortega died in Santo Domingo in 1979. The same year that Hurricane David hit the Dominican Republic. {{Clear}}
